events.description: A group of officials, led by the Western Han minister Huo Guang, present articles of impeachment against the new emperor, Liu He, to the imperial regent, Empress Dowager Shangguan.
events.html: • 74 BC – A group of officials, led by the Western Han minister Huo Guang, present articles of impeachment against the new emperor, Liu He, to the imperial regent, Empress Dowager Shangguan.[1]

events.description: Octavian holds the second of three consecutive triumphs in Rome to celebrate the victory over the Dalmatian tribes.
events.html: • 29 BC – Octavian holds the second of three consecutive triumphs in Rome to celebrate the victory over the Dalmatian tribes.[2]

events.description: King Duncan I is killed in battle against his first cousin and rival Macbeth. The latter succeeds him as King of Scotland.
events.html: • 1040 – King Duncan I is killed in battle against his first cousin and rival Macbeth. The latter succeeds him as King of Scotland.[3]

events.description: Taira no Munemori and the Taira clan take the young Emperor Antoku and the three sacred treasures and flee to western Japan to escape pursuit by the Minamoto clan.
events.html: • 1183 – Taira no Munemori and the Taira clan take the young Emperor Antoku and the three sacred treasures and flee to western Japan to escape pursuit by the Minamoto clan.[4][5]

events.description: After tricking the Venetian galley fleet into sailing east to the Levant, the Genoese capture an entire Venetian trade convoy at the Battle of Saseno.
events.html: • 1264 – After tricking the Venetian galley fleet into sailing east to the Levant, the Genoese capture an entire Venetian trade convoy at the Battle of Saseno.[6]

events.description: War of the Breton Succession: Anglo-Bretons defeat the French in the Battle of Mauron.
events.html: • 1352 – War of the Breton Succession: Anglo-Bretons defeat the French in the Battle of Mauron.[7]

events.description: Charles IV, Holy Roman Emperor, grants city privileges to Karlovy Vary.
events.html: • 1370 – Charles IV, Holy Roman Emperor, grants city privileges to Karlovy Vary.[8]

events.description: Portuguese Crisis of 1383–85: Battle of Aljubarrota: Portuguese forces commanded by John I of Portugal defeat the Castilian army of John I of Castile.
events.html: • 1385 – Portuguese Crisis of 1383–85: Battle of Aljubarrota: Portuguese forces commanded by John I of Portugal defeat the Castilian army of John I of Castile.[9]

events.description: The first sighting of the Falkland Islands by John Davis.
events.html: • 1592 – The first sighting of the Falkland Islands by John Davis.[10]

events.description: Nine Years' War: Battle of the Yellow Ford: Irish forces under Hugh O'Neill, Earl of Tyrone, defeat an English expeditionary force under Henry Bagenal.
events.html: • 1598 – Nine Years' War: Battle of the Yellow Ford: Irish forces under Hugh O'Neill, Earl of Tyrone, defeat an English expeditionary force under Henry Bagenal.[11]

events.description: The Spanish military Villasur expedition is defeated by Pawnee and Otoe warriors near present-day Columbus, Nebraska.
events.html: • 1720 – The Spanish military Villasur expedition is defeated by Pawnee and Otoe warriors near present-day Columbus, Nebraska.[12]

events.description: Russian colonization of North America: Awa’uq Massacre: The Russian fur trader Grigory Shelikhov storms a Kodiak Island Alutiit refuge rock on Sitkalidak Island, killing 500+ Alutiit.
events.html: • 1784 – Russian colonization of North America: Awa’uq Massacre: The Russian fur trader Grigory Shelikhov storms a Kodiak Island Alutiit refuge rock on Sitkalidak Island, killing 500+ Alutiit.[13]

events.description: The Treaty of Wereloe ended the 1788–1790 Russo-Swedish War.
events.html: • 1790 – The Treaty of Wereloe ended the 1788–1790 Russo-Swedish War.[14]

events.description: Slaves from plantations in Saint-Domingue hold a Vodou ceremony led by houngan Dutty Boukman at Bois Caïman, marking the start of the Haitian Revolution.
events.html: • 1791 – Slaves from plantations in Saint-Domingue hold a Vodou ceremony led by houngan Dutty Boukman at Bois Caïman, marking the start of the Haitian Revolution.[15]

events.description: A cease fire agreement, called the Convention of Moss, ended the Swedish–Norwegian War.
events.html: • 1814 – A cease fire agreement, called the Convention of Moss, ended the Swedish–Norwegian War.[16]

events.description: The United Kingdom formally annexes the Tristan da Cunha archipelago, administering the islands from the Cape Colony in South Africa.
events.html: • 1816 – The United Kingdom formally annexes the Tristan da Cunha archipelago, administering the islands from the Cape Colony in South Africa.[17]

events.description: American Indian Wars: Second Seminole War ends, with the Seminoles forced from Florida.
events.html: • 1842 – American Indian Wars: Second Seminole War ends, with the Seminoles forced from Florida.[18]

events.description: Oregon Territory is organized by act of Congress.
events.html: • 1848 – Oregon Territory is organized by act of Congress.[19]

events.description: Construction of Cologne Cathedral, the most famous landmark in Cologne, Germany, is completed.
events.html: • 1880 – Construction of Cologne Cathedral, the most famous landmark in Cologne, Germany, is completed.[20]

events.description: Japan's first patent is issued to the inventor of a rust-proof paint.
events.html: • 1885 – Japan's first patent is issued to the inventor of a rust-proof paint.[21]

events.description: France becomes the first country to introduce motor vehicle registration.
events.html: • 1893 – France becomes the first country to introduce motor vehicle registration.[22]

events.description: Battle of Peking: The Eight-Nation Alliance occupies Beijing, China, in a campaign to end the bloody Boxer Rebellion in China.
events.html: • 1900 – Battle of Peking: The Eight-Nation Alliance occupies Beijing, China, in a campaign to end the bloody Boxer Rebellion in China.[23]

events.description: The first claimed powered flight, by Gustave Whitehead in his Number 21.
events.html: • 1901 – The first claimed powered flight, by Gustave Whitehead in his Number 21.[24]

events.description: World War I: Start of the Battle of Lorraine, an unsuccessful French offensive.
events.html: • 1914 – World War I: Start of the Battle of Lorraine, an unsuccessful French offensive.[25]

events.description: World War I: The Republic of China, which had heretofore been shipping labourers to Europe to assist in the war effort, officially declares war on the Central Powers, although it will continue to send to Europe labourers instead of combatants for the remaining duration of the war.
events.html: • 1917 – World War I: The Republic of China, which had heretofore been shipping labourers to Europe to assist in the war effort, officially declares war on the Central Powers, although it will continue to send to Europe labourers instead of combatants for the remaining duration of the war.[26]

events.description: The 1920 Summer Olympics, having started four months earlier, officially open in Antwerp, Belgium, with the newly adopted Olympic flag and the Olympic oath being raised and taken at the Opening Ceremony for the first time in Olympic history.
events.html: • 1920 – The 1920 Summer Olympics, having started four months earlier, officially open in Antwerp, Belgium, with the newly adopted Olympic flag and the Olympic oath being raised and taken at the Opening Ceremony for the first time in Olympic history.[27][28]

events.description: Tannu Uriankhai, later Tuvan People's Republic is established as a completely independent country (which is supported by Soviet Russia).
events.html: • 1921 – Tannu Uriankhai, later Tuvan People's Republic is established as a completely independent country (which is supported by Soviet Russia).[29]

events.description: Loggers cause a forest fire in the Coast Range of Oregon, later known as the first forest fire of the Tillamook Burn;  destroying 240,000 acres (970 km2) of land.
events.html: • 1933 – Loggers cause a forest fire in the Coast Range of Oregon, later known as the first forest fire of the Tillamook Burn; destroying 240,000 acres (970 km2) of land.[30]

events.description: Franklin D. Roosevelt signs the Social Security Act, creating a government pension system for the retired.
events.html: • 1935 – Franklin D. Roosevelt signs the Social Security Act, creating a government pension system for the retired.[31]

events.description: Rainey Bethea is hanged in Owensboro, Kentucky in the last known public execution in the United States.
events.html: • 1936 – Rainey Bethea is hanged in Owensboro, Kentucky in the last known public execution in the United States.[32]

entities.name: Capital punishment in the United States

events.description: World War II: Winston Churchill and Franklin D. Roosevelt sign the Atlantic Charter of war stating postwar aims.
events.html: • 1941 – World War II: Winston Churchill and Franklin D. Roosevelt sign the Atlantic Charter of war stating postwar aims.[33]

events.description: Pakistan gains independence from the British Empire as the Dominion of Pakistan, due to the partition of India.
events.html: • 1947 – Pakistan gains independence from the British Empire as the Dominion of Pakistan, due to the partition of India.[34]

events.description: An Idaho Department of Fish and Game program to relocate beavers known as Beaver drop occurred. This program relocated beavers from Northwestern Idaho to Central Idaho by airplane and then parachuting the beavers into the Chamberlain Basin .
events.html: • 1948 – An Idaho Department of Fish and Game program to relocate beavers known as Beaver drop occurred. This program relocated beavers from Northwestern Idaho to Central Idaho by airplane and then parachuting the beavers into the Chamberlain Basin .[35]

entities.name: Idaho Department of Fish and Game

events.description: Founding and first official meeting of the American Football League.
events.html: • 1959 – Founding and first official meeting of the American Football League.[36]

events.description: UK Marine Broadcasting Offences Act 1967 declares participation in offshore pirate radio illegal.
events.html: • 1967 – UK Marine Broadcasting Offences Act 1967 declares participation in offshore pirate radio illegal.[37]

events.description: The Troubles: British troops are deployed in Northern Ireland as political and sectarian violence breaks out, marking the start of the 37-year Operation Banner.
events.html: • 1969 – The Troubles: British troops are deployed in Northern Ireland as political and sectarian violence breaks out, marking the start of the 37-year Operation Banner.[38]

events.description: Bahrain declares independence from Britain.
events.html: • 1971 – Bahrain declares independence from Britain.[39]

events.description: An Ilyushin Il-62 airliner crashes near Königs Wusterhausen, East Germany killing 156 people.
events.html: • 1972 – An Ilyushin Il-62 airliner crashes near Königs Wusterhausen, East Germany killing 156 people.[40]

events.description: Lech Wałęsa leads strikes at the Gdańsk, Poland shipyards.
events.html: • 1980 – Lech Wałęsa leads strikes at the Gdańsk, Poland shipyards.[41]

events.description: Ilich Ramírez Sánchez, also known as "Carlos the Jackal", is captured.
events.html: • 1994 – Ilich Ramírez Sánchez, also known as "Carlos the Jackal", is captured.[42]

events.description: Greek Cypriot refugee Solomos Solomou is shot and killed by a Turkish security officer while trying to climb a flagpole in order to remove a Turkish flag from its mast in the United Nations Buffer Zone in Cyprus.
events.html: • 1996 – Greek Cypriot refugee Solomos Solomou is shot and killed by a Turkish security officer while trying to climb a flagpole in order to remove a Turkish flag from its mast in the United Nations Buffer Zone in Cyprus.[43]

entities.name: United Nations Buffer Zone in Cyprus

events.description: A widescale power blackout affects the northeast United States and Canada.
events.html: • 2003 – A widescale power blackout affects the northeast United States and Canada.[44]

events.description: Helios Airways Flight 522, en route from Larnaca, Cyprus to Prague, Czech Republic via Athens, crashes in the hills near Grammatiko, Greece, killing 121 passengers and crew.
events.html: • 2005 – Helios Airways Flight 522, en route from Larnaca, Cyprus to Prague, Czech Republic via Athens, crashes in the hills near Grammatiko, Greece, killing 121 passengers and crew.[45]

events.description: Lebanon War: A ceasefire takes effect three days after the United Nations Security Council’s approval of United Nations Security Council Resolution 1701, formally ending hostilities between Lebanon and Israel.
events.html: • 2006 – Lebanon War: A ceasefire takes effect three days after the United Nations Security Council’s approval of United Nations Security Council Resolution 1701, formally ending hostilities between Lebanon and Israel.[46]

events.description: Sri Lankan Civil War: Sixty-one schoolgirls killed in Chencholai bombing by Sri Lankan Air Force air strike.
events.html: • 2006 – Sri Lankan Civil War: Sixty-one schoolgirls killed in Chencholai bombing by Sri Lankan Air Force air strike.[47]

events.description: The Kahtaniya bombings kill at least 500 people.
events.html: • 2007 – The Kahtaniya bombings kill at least 500 people.[48]

events.description: Egypt declares a state of emergency as security forces kill hundreds of demonstrators supporting former president Mohamed Morsi.
events.html: • 2013 – Egypt declares a state of emergency as security forces kill hundreds of demonstrators supporting former president Mohamed Morsi.[49]

events.description: UPS Airlines Flight 1354 crashes short of the runway at Birmingham–Shuttlesworth International Airport, killing both crew members on board.
events.html: • 2013 – UPS Airlines Flight 1354 crashes short of the runway at Birmingham–Shuttlesworth International Airport, killing both crew members on board.[50]

events.description: The U.S. Embassy in Havana, Cuba re-opens after 54 years of being closed when Cuba–United States relations were broken off.
events.html: • 2015 – The U.S. Embassy in Havana, Cuba re-opens after 54 years of being closed when Cuba–United States relations were broken off.[51]

entities.name: Embassy of the United States, Havana

events.description: The collapse of the Ponte Morandi bridge in Genoa, Italy, left 16 people injured and 43 people killed.
events.html: • 2018 – The collapse of the Ponte Morandi bridge in Genoa, Italy, left 16 people injured and 43 people killed.[52][53]

events.description: A magnitude 7.2 earthquake strikes southwestern Haiti, killing at least 2,248 people and causing a humanitarian crisis.
events.html: • 2021 – A magnitude 7.2 earthquake strikes southwestern Haiti, killing at least 2,248 people and causing a humanitarian crisis.[54]

events.description: An explosion destroys a market in Armenia, killing six people and injuring dozens.
events.html: • 2022 – An explosion destroys a market in Armenia, killing six people and injuring dozens.[55]

events.html: • 2023 – Former U.S. President Donald Trump is charged in Georgia along with 18 others in attempting to overturn the results of the 2020 election in that state, his fourth indictment of 2023.[56]
